  "opinion": "As a carpenter with a master’s degree and a deep curiosity about human behavior, I’ve observed how stereotypes can silently undermine people’s potential. Stereotype threat in STEM isn’t just a theoretical concept—it’s a lived reality for many who feel their identities clash with the expectations of their fields. For instance, when a young woman in my community tries to explain her interest in engineering to her father, he might assume she’s only interested in it because she’s ‘not good at math.’ That kind of subtle bias can make someone question their own abilities long before they even enter a classroom. I’ve seen it in my own children’s education too—my daughter, who’s passionate about physics, sometimes hesitates to share her ideas because she fears being judged as ‘not a math person.’\n\nShould we address it? Absolutely. But not with top-down policies that ignore the cultural context of communities like ours. In Lecce, where we value practical skills and hands-on work, we can start by creating spaces where everyone feels safe to explore without fear of being labeled. For example, local workshops where students from all backgrounds can experiment with building projects together, without the pressure of formal tests or grades. This isn’t about changing the system overnight—it’s about nurturing confidence through small, consistent actions. I believe the key is to empower individuals to see themselves as capable, not as exceptions to a stereotype. My own experience as a curious, hands-on learner taught me that when people feel supported, they thrive. So yes, we must address stereotype threat in STEM, but in ways that respect the traditions and values of our communities—because true progress happens when everyone feels they belong.",
